\par
\b\fs24 TDK's IDE For Dark Basic Professional\par
\b0\fs20\par
Thanks for downloading my DBPro IDE. It is not an official replacement for the existing IDE (written by Guy Savoie), but simply an alternative. I started producing it as a back-burner project a long time before Guy left the DB community and we subsequently discovered that the official IDE was no longer being worked on. I basically wanted a simple \b multi-document \b0 interface - that's all!  This program is the result.\par
\par
\par
\b\fs24 No Huge Downloads Required!\par
\b0\fs20\par
This IDE is a totally stand-alone exe file. It requires \b no \b0 additional files or anything extra to be installed on your computer. As such, there are no hefty downloads to worry about or wierd DLL's to locate and install. Just unzip and run!\par
\par
\par
\b\fs24 Aims:\par
\b0\fs20\par
I never used many of the advanced features of the official IDE - I prefer a simple environment. As such, the intention is to keep bells and whistles to a bare minimum. Create or load, edit, copy and paste from other windows, save, compile and finally run. That's all I personally need. \par
\par
This IDE when finished will probably have little more than that and requests for additional features will only be considered if I would use them myself.\par
\par
\par
\b\fs24 IMPORTANT INFO  (In case you skip the rest of this readme): \par
\b0\fs20\par
\cf3\b Please remember though that in it's current state it's only a taster and that although usable, it is neither finished or bug free. REMEMBER ALSO that if you are upgrading an earlier version, \cf4 ALWAYS delete the file C:\\TDK_IDE.INI before running the new version\cf3 .\par
\cf4\par
\cf3 And, \cf4 PLEASE READ THE KNOWN ISSUES SECTION AT THE END OF THIS DOCUMENT \cf3 - even if you don't read any of the rest! \par
\par
This IDE MUST be placed in the Dark Basic Professional\\Editor folder as it uses the DBPro DLL. If you put it elsewhere it will not work!\par
\cf0\b0\par
Finally, you may only use it \b AT YOUR OWN RISK \b0 and if you do not agree to this, please do not use it at all.\par
\par
\par
\b\fs24 Installation:\par
\b0\fs20\par
This program does \b not \b0 have any installation and does not make any changes to your system - it simply replaces the existing IDE and uses the system settings already in place for it. All you do is copy the supplied file EDITOR.EXE to the same folder that your existing editor was located.\par
\par
\par
\cf1\b\fs24 Advanced Installation Instructions (For more experienced users):\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
1. Rename the existing Editor.Exe to OldEditor.Exe\par
2. Copy the new editor.exe and \cf5 Language \cf0 folder into the \cf5 Dark Basic Professional\\Editor \cf0 Folder\par
3. To uninstall, delete the new Editor.Exe and rename the original one back to Editor.Exe\par
\par
\par
\cf1\b\fs24 In Depth Installation Instructions (For less experienced users):\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
\cf4\b IMPORTANT\cf0\b0\par
\par
This editor has the same filename as the existing one, so you \b MUST \b0 rename your existing editor before copying this one. If you don't, you won't be able to go back to the original one after trying this one out. If when you copy this editor you get a message telling you that Editor.exe already exists and asks you if it's OK to overwrite it, say \b NO \b0 and rename the existing file first.\par
\par
\b\fs22 How To Rename Editor.Exe: \fs24\par
\b0\fs20\par
Using Windows Explorer, locate your \cf5 Dark Basic Professional \cf0 folder. Inside it, you will see a folder called \cf5 Editor\cf0 . \par
\par
Inside there will be three folders and two files - one of which is the current IDE called \cf1 EDITOR.EXE\cf0 . \b Right click \b0 on this and choose \b rename \b0 from the pop-up menu.\par
\par
Simply add 'old' to the start of the filename to make it \cf1 OLDEDITOR.EXE \cf0 ( or \cf1 OLDEDITOR\cf0  if your settings currently have filename extensions hidden). It doesn't really matter what you name it, so long as it's not called Editor.exe any more. As a test, try running DBP now. If you have done all this correctly, DBP should \b not \b0 run as the file Editor.Exe no longer exists.\par
\par
You can now copy the new Editor.Exe file and the folder \cf5 Language \cf0 into the Editor folder. That's it!\par
\par
To remove this editor and go back to the old one, simply use Windows Explorer to delete Editor.Exe and rename the previous one (OldEditor.Exe) back to Editor.Exe.\par
\par
\par
\b\fs24 Using The New IDE:\par
\b0\fs20\par
When first run, you will need to enter a few details. This is done only once and what you enter can be changed from the tools menu entry later on if necessary. Also, some options are not working yet - remember this IDE is still in a basic state at the moment, so only play with copies of your files - not the originals.\par
\par
\par
\cf2\b\fs28 Instructions For Use:\par
\cf0\b0\fs20\par
Most of it is pretty standard stuff, so I'll only cover the not so obvious stuff here.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b Screen Layout\par
\cf0\b0\par
At the top of the screen, there is the menu bar. All options are available from drop-down menus.\par
\par
Just below the menu bar are the Speed Buttons allowing quick access to the more commonly used functions such as loading and saving. Hold the mouse over a button for a second or so and a description of the button will pop up. The speed buttons running from left to right across the top are as follows:\par
\par
New Project/File\par
Open Project\par
Open DBA Source\par
Save Project\par
Save DBA Source\par
Save DBA Source As...\par
Save All\par
Compile Source\tab\tab\tab\tab\tab\tab F4\par
Compile & Run\tab\tab\tab\tab\tab\tab F5\par
Run In Debug Mode\tab\tab\tab\tab\tab F6\par
Run In StepThrough Mode (Is this really needed)?\tab\tab F7\par
Run Existing Exe (Without Compiling)\tab\tab\tab F8\par
Show/Hide Project Panel\par
Help\par
Switch Between DBPro & DBC Modes\tab\tab\tab\par
Exit\par
\par
\par
The large area below this is available for you program window(s). \par
\par
At the bottom, is the status bar where information and messages appear. When multiple source files are open, this panel updates to reflect the settings of the currently selected window.\par
\par
Although at first invisible, on the right of the screen appears the project settings panel. This can be quickly toggled by the 'Show/Hide Project Panel' speed button as well as via the menu. Some (but not all) of this info is even used if you are using DB Classic!\par
\par
\cf5\b\par
File Saving Security\par
\cf0\b0\par
The IDE has two levels of security for your files:\par
\par
1. When you save your source code, the editor automatically creates a backup of the .DBA file with the same name, but with the extension .BAK.\par
\par
2. When you modify and Compile/Run your new code without saving it first, should your computer crash and require a reset, your new modifications will be lost. Now, each time you successfully compile or run, the IDE creates a file called LastCompiled.dba. This file will always be only one compile/run phase behind the code you lost and you can reload this and save it out with your project name in an emergency.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b DBPro/DBC Support\par
\cf0\b0\par
The IDE now supports Dark Basic Classic too. When first run, you are now able to enter both the DBPro compiler location and the location of Dark Basic Classic's DB.EXE file. Separate Project folder locations for each can be entered. If you do not have both versions of DB, then leave the two relevant boxes empty.\par
\par
Also on this panel in the bottom left corner are two check boxes which allow you to set the default running mode of the IDE. This setting is the mode the IDE enters when it is run. You can switch the mode with the Mode speed button, but it does not affect the default setting for the next time the IDE is run.\par
\par
These settings can be changed at any time by selecting 'System Options' from the Tools menu.\par
\par
The mode speed button at the top of the screen shows which mode you are currently in and the status bar will show DBP when in Pro mode and DBC when in Classic mode.\par
\par
With this, you can load a DBC source file, run it in DBC, click the mode button and instantly run it with the DBPro compiler!\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b Multiple Windows\par
\cf0\b0\par
You can open multiple source windows to copy and paste code between them. The Project Panel is updated as you switch between them, so hitting the compile or run buttons will compile or run the project in the currently selected window.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b Goto Line Number\par
\cf0\b0\par
Press Ctrl-G. Enter the required line number and press Enter or click on the OK button.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b Bookmarks\par
\cf0\b0\par
Left click on the line number margin running down the left side of the screen. If none is present already, a bookmark will appear. If there is one on that line already, it will be turned off. You can have up to 10 bookmarks and if you try to create another, nothing will happen and you will have to turn one of the existing bookmarks off.\par
\par
To jump to a bookmark, press Ctrl-B. Bookmarks available have a lit green LED next to them. Simply click on the required bookmark button to jump to that bookmark. If you select a bookmark that is not lit, then nothing will happen.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b Code Templates\par
\cf0\b0\par
A number of templates are available for inserting block commands. These are the commands which define blocks of code and have a start and end, like For...Next, Repeat...Until and While...EndWhile. Using a template, means that you never forget to put a Next, Until or EndWhile ever again as the layout is entered for you!\par
\par
To add a template, left click to place the cursor where you want the code template to be placed, then click the right mouse button. A pop-up will appear listing the currently available templates. Select the required template with the left mouse button.\par
\par
A parameter panel will appear. This panel contains all the parameters for all the templates, but only the one you selected will appear in red. The rest will be disabled.\par
\par
In this section, you can enter the parameters you require in the template. For example, if you selected For...Next loop, then there will be boxes to enter in the desired counter variable, the start and end value for counting, as well as the optional Step value. Whatever you enter in these boxes will appear in the template frame back in the source window. Once you have entered the parameters, click the small OK button in the respective parameter section. \par
\par
If you enter A in the variable name box, 1 for the start value and 10 for the end value, clicking the OK button will produce:\par
\par
\cf1 For A=1 To 10\par
\par
Next A\par
\cf0\par
To exit this panel without creating a template, click on the Cancel button.\par
\par
If you would rather create an empty template with no parameters, then select the checkbox in the bottom left corner of the panel. The parameters will still be remembered, so you can return later, remove the check mark and use the same parameters again. With the check mark ticked, the same For...Next example will create:\par
\par
\cf1 For  =   To\par
\par
Next \par
\cf0\par
and you must manually enter the missing parameters.\par
\par
The same section is used for both procedures and functions, but only the first parameter is used for procedures. If parameters are entered into the other two boxes, they are ignored if not using the function template.\par
\par
\b\par
\cf5 Project Panel\par
\cf0\b0\par
The project panel lets you enter information about the current project. This IDE also creates a .dbpro file for DB Classic files so you can store info, though some options will obviously not be usable. Project panel options include:\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b Comments\par
\cf0\b0\par
These are now saved with the project when you save it. Make notes about the project in this section.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b To Do List\par
\cf0\b0\par
This is a list of reminders to jog your memory when you are working on a project - like 'Don't forget to remove debug code at line 224' for example. \par
\par
To add a new To Do item, right mouse click in the To Do window and select Add New Item from the pop-up panel that appears. Enter your item in the box that appears and click on OK.\par
\par
Each item has a tickbox next to it, so you can tick off the items when you have completed them. The other items on the pop-up are pretty obvious.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b Variables, Functions & Labels\par
\cf0\b0\par
These items are scanned in from the source code itself - you cannot alter the contents of the windows themselves, as they merely reflect what is in the source code itself.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b Graphics Mode Settings \par
\cf0\b0\par
Use this section to set the required graphics mode for your project.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b External Files\par
\cf0\b0\par
This option is not yet implemented (next version). For now, simply use #Include.\par
\par
\par
\cf5\b Toolbox Modules\par
\cf0\b0\par
This is available from the Tools menu, thogh there are only two modules available at the moment - Remove Indentation and Indent Source code.\par
\par
Remove Indentation will remove all the indentation in the currently selected source window. All the code will be flush aginst the left edge of the window.\par
\par
Indent Source code will automatically indent all block sections of code like For Next loops.\par
\par
\par
\par
